Q.3. Explain in your own words the difference between storing data in a simple key-value store (like Hive) versus a structured relational database (like SQLite), using an example from any app you use daily (such as playlists in Spotify or orders in Swiggy).

Ans:-

Hive and SQLite are both used to store data,
but they work in different ways and are suitable for different types of information.

Hive is a key-value database that stores data as simple key-value pairs. 
It is lightweight, fast, and does not require SQL queries or tables. 
Hive is commonly used to save small pieces of data such as app settings, login information, theme preferences, or favorite items.

SQLite is a relational database that stores data in tables with rows and columns. 
It supports SQL queries and is ideal for handling structured data where different tables are related to each other.
